'''Abhorrent''', ''[[adjective (part of speech)|adjective]]'' [L. ''abhorens'', ''-rentis'', p. pr. of ''abhorrere''.]

<ol>
<li>[[Abhorring]]; [[detesting]]; having or showing [[abhorrence]]; [[loathing]]; hence, strongly opposed to; as, ''abhorrent'' thoughts.

<code>The persons most ''abhorrent'' from blood and treason. ''[[Burke (source)|Burke]].''</code>

<code>The arts of pleasure in despotic courts I spurn ''abhorrent''. ''[[Clover (source)|Clover]].''</code>

<li> Contrary or [[repugnant]]; [[discordant]]; [[inconsistent]]; -- followed by ''to''.

<code>Injudicious profanation, so ''abhorrent'' to our stricter principles.</code> ''[[Gibbon (source)|Gibbon]].''

<li> [[Detestable]].

<code>Pride, ''abhorrent'' as it is.</code> ''[[I. Taylor (source)|I. Taylor]].''
</ol>